# Wattwise — Dynamic Tariff Engine

A Laravel-based, database-driven tariff engine for utility billing. Tariffs are defined per country and category (residential / industrial) as **versioned, contiguous tier ladders**, managed from a Filament admin dashboard. All financial math is deterministic and happens in the backend — never inside an LLM.

This module is the pricing core of **Wattwise**, an AI-powered electricity billing optimizer. The AI layer only *narrates* pre-calculated results; this engine is the single source of truth for every number a user sees.

## Design principles (locked)

| # | Principle | What it means in practice |
|---|-----------|---------------------------|
| 1 | **Set-level versioning** | A tariff is versioned as a whole ladder. A `TariffVersion` parent owns the effective date range; `Tier` children never carry their own dates. The calculator resolves *one* version per (country, category, date), then iterates its tiers. |
| 2 | **Half-open intervals `[min, max)`** | Every tier covers `min_kwh` inclusive to `max_kwh` exclusive. Adjacent tiers share a boundary exactly. Consumption landing exactly on a boundary belongs to the **higher** tier — never both, never neither. The top tier is open-ended (`max_kwh = NULL`). |
| 3 | **DECIMAL everywhere, floats nowhere** | Prices and kWh are stored as `DECIMAL`, cast to strings by Eloquent, and compared/computed via **bcmath**. The final amount is rounded **once**, to the country's minor-unit scale. |
| 4 | **Timezone-aware effective dates** | `effective_from` / `effective_to` are `timestamptz`. Version resolution happens in the *country's* local timezone, not UTC. |
| 5 | **Append-only usage logs** | `usage_logs` rows are immutable (enforced at the model level). Corrections are new rows pointing at the row they supersede via `supersedes_id`, with a mandatory `correction_reason`. Daily granularity preserves the option of prorated mid-cycle billing later. |

## Schema

```
countries
├── code (unique, ISO 3166-1)        e.g. "SA", "SY"
├── currency_code (ISO 4217)         e.g. "SAR", "SYP"
├── currency_minor_unit_scale        final rounding precision
└── timezone (IANA)                  e.g. "Asia/Riyadh"

tariff_versions                      ← the versioned ladder (parent)
├── country_id → countries
├── category                         "residential" | "industrial"
├── effective_from / effective_to    half-open range, timestamptz, NULL = open-ended
└── label                            e.g. "SA residential 2026 Q2"

tiers                                ← ladder rows (children, cascade on delete)
├── tariff_version_id → tariff_versions
├── sort_order
├── min_kwh / max_kwh                DECIMAL(12,3); max NULL only on the last tier
└── price_per_kwh                    DECIMAL(12,6)

usage_logs                           ← daily granularity, append-only
├── user_id, usage_date, consumption_kwh
├── supersedes_id → usage_logs      corrections chain, never UPDATE
└── correction_reason               required when superseding
```

On **PostgreSQL**, the migrations add defense-in-depth constraints on top of app-level validation:

- a `gist` **exclusion constraint** making overlapping effective ranges for the same (country, category) impossible to insert (`btree_gist` extension, created automatically);
- check constraints for `price_per_kwh >= 0` and `min_kwh < max_kwh`.

## Ladder validation

`App\Services\TariffLadderValidator` is the authoritative, framework-agnostic validator. A ladder is rejected unless **all** of the following hold:

- strictly ascending by `sort_order` / `min_kwh`
- the first tier starts at exactly `0`
- adjacent tiers are contiguous: tier N's `max_kwh` **equals** tier N+1's `min_kwh` (no gaps, no overlaps)
- exactly **one** open-ended tier, and it is the **last** one
- `min_kwh < max_kwh` within every bounded tier
- `price_per_kwh >= 0` everywhere

Errors come back keyed by field (`tiers.{index}.{field}`), so they map cleanly onto Filament Repeater rows.

`App\Rules\ContiguousTariffLadder` is the thin Laravel `ValidationRule` wrapper for form usage:

```php
use App\Rules\ContiguousTariffLadder;

Forms\Components\Repeater::make('tiers')
    ->schema([
        Forms\Components\TextInput::make('min_kwh')->numeric()->required(),
        Forms\Components\TextInput::make('max_kwh')->numeric()
            ->helperText('Leave empty on the last tier (open-ended).'),
        Forms\Components\TextInput::make('price_per_kwh')->numeric()->required(),
        Forms\Components\Hidden::make('sort_order'),
    ])
    ->orderColumn('sort_order')
    ->rule(new ContiguousTariffLadder());
```

An invalid ladder cannot be saved — a whole `TariffVersion` (parent + tiers) publishes atomically or not at all.

## Version resolution

The calculator never assembles a ladder from independently-dated rows. It resolves one version, then reads its tiers:

```php
use App\Models\TariffVersion;

// Convert the billing period's reference date into the COUNTRY's timezone first
// (locked decision #4), then resolve:
$version = TariffVersion::query()
    ->forCountryCategory($country->id, TariffVersion::CATEGORY_RESIDENTIAL)
    ->effectiveAt($periodEnd->setTimezone($country->timezone))
    ->with('tiers')          // tiers come back in ladder order
    ->first();

// No version covering the date? That's a hard NO_ACTIVE_TARIFF error —
// the calculator must never guess or fall back to a default.
```

## Example ladders

**Saudi Arabia — residential, monthly:**

| Tier | Range (kWh) | Price |
|------|-------------|-------|
| 1 | `[0, 6000)` | 0.18 SAR |
| 2 | `[6000, ∞)` | 0.30 SAR |

Consumption of exactly **6,000 kWh**: the first 6,000 kWh fill tier 1 (`[0, 6000)` holds 6,000 whole kWh: 0 through 5,999.999), and the boundary value itself marks the start of tier 2. The half-open convention makes this unambiguous — no kWh is ever counted twice.

**Syria — residential, bimonthly:**

| Tier | Range (kWh) | Price |
|------|-------------|-------|
| 1 | `[0, 300)` | 600 SYP |
| 2 | `[300, ∞)` | 1400 SYP |

## Installation

```bash
# copy migrations, models, rules, and services into your Laravel app, then:
php artisan migrate
```

Requirements:

- PHP ≥ 8.2 with **ext-bcmath**
- Laravel 11+
- PostgreSQL recommended (exclusion constraints); MySQL works with app-level validation only
- Filament v3 for the admin resource

